	Fort Worth (Texas): Former Olympic champion Marion Jones, sentenced in January to six months in prison for lying about using steroids, has reported to a Texas jail, US bureau of prisons spokeswoman Traci Billingsley said.    
	Yes, thats confirmed, Billingsley said, adding that the 32-year-old athlete reported shortly before noon to the Federal Medical Center-Carswell, a correctional facility in fort worth, where she was assigned the inmate number 84868/054.    
	Jones, who has been stripped of the three gold and two bronze medals she won at the 2000 Sydney Olympics, was sentenced to six months in jail and two years of probation for lying to federal investigators about her use of performance-enhancing drugs and about a check-fraud scheme that involved her former partner  Tim Montgomery.       
	London: Former England midfielder Paul Gascoigne has been released from a clinic after being held under the Mental Health Act since February 20, British media reported on Friday.    
	The former Tottenham Hotspur, Newcastle United, Rangers and Lazio player, widely known as Gazza, had been detained after being arrested at a hotel in Newcastle, north-east England.    
	The 40-year-old, who won 57 caps between 1988 and 1998, made international headlines during the 1990 World Cup in Italy after crying following a yellow card in Englands semi-final defeat by West Germany which would have seen him suspended for the final.         
	Madrid: A prankster pretending to be Oscar-winning American actor Nicolas Cage fooled Real Madrid into thinking he was the real thing and enjoyed red carpet treatment at this weeks Champions League match against AS Roma.    
	The lookalike, Italian television presenter Paolo Calabresi, watched Wednesdays game from the directors viewing area at the Bernabeu and was taken into the team dressing room afterwards, a Spanish sports daily reported on Saturday.        
	Palm Harbor (US): For all the tough losses he has endured on the golf course the last few years, Ernie Els found perspective at home in the blue eyes of five-year-old Ben.    
	His son was diagnosed with autism, which Els and his wife coped with privately until the South African showed up on the USPGA Tour this week with an Autism speaks logo on his golf bag and a message he wanted to get out.    
	I feel comfortable talking about it now, Els said after he missed the cut in the Pods Championship on Friday.         
	New Delhi: Karan Rastogis doubles campaign in the ITF Futures tournament in Abidjan, Ivory Coast, ended on Saturday as he and Alexander Satschko were upset by Russians Ilya Belyaev and Sergei Krotiouk 6-2, 6-7(5), 12-14 in the semi-final.    
	Rastogi had earlier crashed out of the singles with a 6-7(4), 6-1, 1-6 quarter-final loss to Valentin Sanon.         
	New Delhi: The Dalai Lama, the spiritual head of Tibetan Buddhists, expressed his support for the Beijing Olympics on Saturday, rejecting Chinese allegations that he was trying to sabotage the games.    
	His holiness the Dalai Lama has always supported the Beijing Olympics and he reaffirms this again, Chime Chhoekyapa, the Dalai Lamas secretary said.        
